{"type":"message","id":"d82cc8cb","parentId":"b4fc841a","timestamp":"2026-04-19T07:57:44.448Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the MDX file is at `content/articles/ai/linear-regression-python.mdx` and has `category: \"ai\"`. The slug extracted from filename is `linear-regression-python`. The URL should be `/articles/linear-regression-python`. And `getArticleBySlug` should recursively find `ai/linear-regression-python.mdx`.\n\nBut wait - maybe the NEXT BUILD is using stale data? The build was done before my fix was applied. Actually no, I committed the fix and rebuilt before starting the server.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The error says:\n```\nENOENT: no such file or directory, open '/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/maiy-tech-hub/content/articles/linear-regression-python.mdx'\n\n\n```\n\nThis is the raw file path - no subdirectory. This means `getArticleBySlug` is NOT using the recursive find. Either the recursive find isn't in the running code, or it's failing silently. But I'm using `fs.existsSync` as a fallback - let me check if that's being hit instead.\n\nLooking at the current code, there's no `fs.existsSync` fallback at all. So the running server must have an older version without the recursive find. I did restart the server after the build, so it should be running the latest code. Let me test the article detail directly to see what's actually happening.\n\n```","thinkingSignature":"9ca4a093b2121112801ebce0b11bc28a3aa0bcf9fdc297492de5bd543b1a7157"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_f91ge75xwx7t_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\" http://localhost:3000/articles/linear-regression-python","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":271,"output":350,"cacheRead":64766,"cacheWrite":1316,"totalTokens":66703,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"st